    description = 'A comprehensive scholarly examination of the Yazidi religious community through a tripartite analytical framework of facts (haqāʼiq), hidden realities (khafāyā), and legendary narratives (asāṭīr). This 147-page anthropological-religious monograph by Iraqi scholar Zuhayr Kazim Abud (1944-) represents a systematic academic study that combines historical documentation, ethnographic observation, and folkloric analysis to understand the complex syncretic religious system of the Yazidis. The work addresses the authentic nature of Yazidi theology versus popular misconceptions, examining the role of Melek Taus (Peacock Angel) in Yazidi cosmology, sacred texts, priestly hierarchy, esoteric practices, and community defense mechanisms. The study traces ancient Mesopotamian religious continuity, analyzes religious syncretism in Kurdish communities, and explores the intersection of Islamic-Christian-Zoroastrian theological elements. The book deconstructs popular misconceptions including devil worship accusations, examines folkloric traditions and creation myths, and analyzes external perceptions from Islamic heresiographical literature and Christian missionary accounts. This work contributes significantly to minority religious studies, religious syncretism research, and the methodological challenges of studying marginalized religious traditions in the Middle East. The tripartite analytical framework provides a comprehensive scholarly apparatus for understanding how minority religious communities maintain identity while navigating external pressures, making it essential for scholars examining religious diversity and community preservation in the modern Middle East.'
